About
Once the hunting ground for Henry VIII, this large royal park is best known for its famous Speakers' Corner, where people speak their minds, Rotton Row, a famous horse-riding area and Serpentine Lake, home to waterfowl and oarsmen.
Duration: 2-3 hours

Marble Arch
Lancaster Gate
Queensway
Paddington
Bayswater
& More

There is also a lake called Septerine. In the lake you can boat . On the boat , there is a unique steering wheel . On the electric boats , there is just the steering mechanism .
To go left , pull the steering mechanism right . To go right , pull the mechanism left.

There is also the yellow switch . To go forwards , push the switch forward . To go backwards, push the switch backwards. To stop , keep the switch in the middle.

There are a lot of other things to experience in Hyde Park too.

Largest of the Royal Parks in London
Sep 2024 • Solo
Hyde Park is the largest of the Royal Parks of London. It covers an area of around 140 hectares and was first opened to the public back in 1637. Heading deep into the park, you can begin to lose sight and sense of the surrounding city surrounding and begins to feel the rural connection to land and nature. You may see horses being written, dogs and children at play, people enjoying endless grassy fields, tree lined walking paths, picnics under the shade of trees.

Hyde Park is also the sight of points of interest such as Speaker's Corner in the north-east end of the Park, The Long Water, Serpentine Watersheds, The Italian Garden and elegant Princess Diana Memorial Fountain.

Note that Hyde Park butts up against the Kensington Gardens to the west, providing another 107 hectares of rural and green retreat and leisure grounds. Combined you can spend several hours in between the two Royal Parks enjoying relaxed time away from the chaos of the city surrounding you.
